The [Siege of Boston](/Siege_of_Boston), unfolding between April 19, 1775, and March 17, 1776, marked the opening, and arguably the most drawn-out, act of the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) [^5]. It was a rather tedious affair, characterized by a protracted standoff where newly organized [American patriot](/Patriot_(American_Revolution)) militias, eventually coalescing into the [Continental Army](/Continental_Army) under the command of the rather stoic [George Washington](/George_Washington), effectively trapped the seasoned [British Army](/British_Army_during_the_American_Revolutionary_War) within the confines of [Boston](/Boston). The British, accustomed to open warfare, found themselves immobilized by land, reduced to a de facto island garrison.

Both sides, in a display of predictable human inefficiency, grappled with considerable challenges concerning resources, supplies, and personnel throughout the siege. For the British, resupply and reinforcement were strictly confined to sea access, a lifeline that was increasingly, and irritatingly, impeded by the growing number of American vessels. The Americans, for their part, struggled with the organizational chaos inherent in transforming disparate militias into a cohesive fighting force. Ultimately, after nearly a year of this rather unproductive stalemate, the British begrudgingly conceded defeat, abandoning [Boston](/Boston) and relocating their beleaguered troops and equipment further north to the more hospitable, and less hostile, shores of [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia).

The siege's origins trace back to April 19, 1775, immediately following the ignominious British retreat from the Revolutionary War's initial skirmishes at [Lexington and Concord](/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord). Massachusetts militias, brimming with a newfound, if untested, resolve, swiftly moved to block all land routes into [Boston](/Boston). Meanwhile, the [Continental Congress](/Continental_Congress), convening in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), began the arduous task of formalizing these ad-hoc militias into a proper [Continental Army](/Continental_Army), placing [George Washington](/George_Washington) at its head as commander in chief – a decision that, in hindsight, proved rather fortuitous.

June 1775 saw a brief, bloody spasm of activity when the British, in a desperate attempt to break the encirclement, [seized Bunker Hill and Breed's Hill](/Battle_of_Bunker_Hill). These two positions offered a commanding, albeit precarious, view over [Boston](/Boston). While a tactical victory for the British, the engagement came at an exorbitant cost, with roughly 1,160 British casualties against 469 American losses. Their gains, achieved at such a staggering price, were ultimately insufficient to dislodge the [Continental Army](/Continental_Army)'s tenacious encirclement. Following this grim affair, the Americans settled into a more passive, yet equally effective, siege. No further major battles marred the landscape; instead, the conflict devolved into a series of tiresome raids, minor skirmishes, and the occasional, irritating crack of sniper fire. British attempts to provision their garrison were perpetually hampered by the smaller, more agile [Continental Army](/Continental_Army) and other patriot forces operating with surprising effectiveness both on land and at sea. Consequently, the British forces endured a chronic and debilitating lack of food, fuel, and essential supplies – a rather undignified state for His Majesty's finest.

A pivotal shift in this protracted stalemate occurred in November 1775, when [George Washington](/George_Washington), displaying a rare flash of strategic foresight, dispatched [Henry Knox](/Henry_Knox) on a mission of monumental logistical complexity. Knox was tasked with retrieving the heavy artillery recently [captured at Fort Ticonderoga](/Capture_of_Fort_Ticonderoga). In an operation that defied the brutal realities of a New England winter and primitive transportation, Knox, with a seemingly impossible determination, successfully [brought these formidable cannons to Boston](/Noble_train_of_artillery) by January 1776. This newfound firepower was then strategically deployed to [fortify Dorchester Heights](/Fortification_of_Dorchester_Heights), a position that offered an uncomfortably clear, and dangerously close, view of [Boston harbor](/Boston_Harbor) and, crucially, the British supply lifeline from the sea. British commander [William Howe](/William_Howe,_5th_Viscount_Howe), recognizing the sudden and undeniable indefensibility of his position, had little choice but to withdraw his forces from [Boston](/Boston), sailing for [Halifax, Nova Scotia](/Halifax,_Nova_Scotia) on March 17, a day now celebrated by some, and likely forgotten by most.

## Background

Main articles: [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) and [Boston campaign](/Boston_campaign)

The Grand Union flag flown by P. Sherman during the siege of Boston [^6], a rather symbolic banner for a nascent rebellion.
A 1775 map of the [Battles of Lexington and Concord](/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord) and the siege of Boston, illustrating the geographical constraints that would define the conflict.

The seeds of this conflict were sown long before 1775, in the fertile ground of imperial overreach and colonial resentment. The British, in their infinite wisdom, had consistently [imposed taxes and import duties](/Colonial_history_of_the_United_States) upon the American colonies. The Americans, with perhaps a naive expectation of fairness, naturally objected to these levies, citing their fundamental belief that they [lacked proper representation in the British Parliament](/No_taxation_without_representation) – a rather obvious point that somehow eluded an entire empire. These grievances escalated, culminating in acts of defiance such as the infamous [Boston Tea Party](/Boston_Tea_Party) and other assorted protests. The Crown's response was swift and predictably heavy-handed: 4,000 British troops were dispatched to occupy [Boston](/Boston) under the command of General [Thomas Gage](/Thomas_Gage), with the explicit mandate to pacify the increasingly restive [Province of Massachusetts Bay](/Province_of_Massachusetts_Bay) [^7].

Parliament, seemingly determined to rub salt in the wound, further empowered Gage to dismantle the existing government of Massachusetts Bay, then led by the rather obstinate figures of [John Hancock](/John_Hancock) and [Samuel Adams](/Samuel_Adams), among wielding numerous [other punitive powers](/Intolerable_Acts). However, the Americans, exhibiting a stubborn refusal to be governed against their will, simply formed their own parallel government, the [Massachusetts Provincial Congress](/Massachusetts_Provincial_Congress), and continued to convene with defiant regularity. This Provincial Congress, a testament to grassroots organization, then issued calls for the formation of local militias and diligently coordinated the accumulation of weapons and other critical military supplies [^8]. Adding insult to injury, or perhaps simply accelerating the inevitable, Gage, under the terms of the [Boston Port Act](/Boston_Port_Act), closed the port of [Boston](/Boston), a move that predictably caused widespread unemployment and further inflamed colonial discontent [^9].

The powder keg finally ignited on April 19, 1775, when British forces embarked on an ill-fated mission to seize military supplies from the town of [Concord](/Concord,_Massachusetts). Their progress was met with armed opposition from militia companies drawn from the surrounding towns, leading to the pivotal [Battles of Lexington and Concord](/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord) [^10]. At [Concord](/Concord,_Massachusetts), a portion of the British forces found themselves ignominiously routed in a confrontation at the [North Bridge](/Old_North_Bridge). What followed was a brutal, running battle as the British troops attempted to march back to [Boston](/Boston), suffering heavy casualties along the way [^11]. The alarm, a literal call to arms, reverberated throughout [New England](/New_England), prompting militias from all colonies in the region to converge on [Boston](/Boston), effectively setting the stage for the protracted siege [^12].

